 under Windows Phone 7 / Windows 8. The software solution accepts the information input from the glove sensors and transforms the resulting data into a sound wave (Picture 1). The interaction between the glove and the mobile device is implemented through Bluetooth technology. After surveying the existing hardware solutions that attempt the recognition of signs we have decided to make the hardware ourselves. We've created several different prototypes, tested several solutions with flex sensors.%0a%3c %0a%3c http://enabletalk.com:80/images/glove1.jpg%0a%3c %0a%3c As a result we've developed the model of gloves that includes modern microcontroller, 15 flex sensors, accelerometer, gyroscope, and a compass in order to define the position of the glove in space, a Bluetooth module for data transmission from the gloves to a mobile device and a USB-port for the synchronization with the PC and for charging the Li-ion battery that provides power. The glove is also fitted with a solar panel to provide for longer intervals between charging and out of concern for environment.%0a%3c %0a%3c Our team is confident that this project allows us to combine modern technologies in the field of microelectronics and the immense power of Windows OS in order to make the world better not only for people with hearing and speech disabilities, but also for the rest of us. Furthermore, the potential of our system is in no way limited to the described field, but can also be applied in virtually every segment of IT.%0a%3c %0a%3c http://enabletalk.com:80/images/glove2.jpg%0a%3c %0a%3c ! Advantages%0a%3c %0a%3c *'''  Uniq  Easy to use'''%0a%3c %0a%3c *'''  Ultra-portable  Flexible'''%0a%3c %0a%3c *'''  Long battery life  Cheap to produce'''%0a%3c %0a%3c *'''  Large target audience  Phone use possibility'''%0a%3c %0a%3c &copy; 2012. All rights reserved%0a%3c %0a%3c (:linkwikiwords:)%0a
